        <h2>Why are we pursuing Glimpse?</h2>
        <p>The results of our WoZ testing pointed us towards Glimpse not Quack for two big reasons.</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Short glimpse videos are a more effective medium for impression-based communication than 10-second quack video chats</li>
            <ul>
                <li>Quack is about creating brief face-to-face moments, and users generally just said things like "hello how are you". They didn't put much thought into the video they were projecting to their friend because their focus was on watching the video feed from their friend. As a result, the videos were less rich and conveyed less information about the person, her surroundings, etc.</li>
                <li>Users found more and more creative uses for Glimpse videos than Quack. Glimpse is about recording a video message for someone. Users used glimpses to say an animated hello, to deliver a goofy performance, and to show off things around them-- their location or a specific item. </li>
                <li>Because of the performative dimension and the diversity of uses for glimpse videos, using glimpse (both recording your own and receiving from your friends) is funner than watching a 10-second feed of your friend's face as they talk to you.</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Synchronicity can place a real burden on users.</li>
            <ul>
                <li>Having two users be "online" at the same time required co-ordination, set-up, etc</li>
                <li>Many times, when a user tried to schedule a "quack chat", the other user was not available, leading to failed attempts at communication.</li>
                <li>Trying to schedule a 10-sec video chat required attention and effort; very cognitively demanding for what's supposed to be low-friction, impression-based communication</li>
                <li>In user studies we found great opportunities for helping enable communication between people with different levels of motivation for staying in touch (e.g., mom-college kid communication). Synchronous communication requires both parties to be motivated participants. Therefore, it's not a good way to target relationships in which existing communication is asymmetrical. </li>
            </ul>
        </ol>
    </div>  
