        <h2>What does our functional prototype prioritize?</h2>
        <h3>Mobile.</h3>
        <p>Our WoZ testing only worked on desktop devices (because of HTML5 MediaRecorder limitations). This had two crucial implications:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>It limited the space of things you can get a glimpse of, both because laptops are bulkier (harder to take videos of things around you) and because people use laptops in sedentary settings, not when they're on the go and seeing the interesting things that glimpse requesters want glimpses of. Overall, it reduces the freedom of the user providing a glimpse.</li>
            <li>It dramatically reduced the spontaneity of the interaction. Glimpse videos are too short and fleeting to be a hassle. Restricting the glimpse medium to laptops increases the burden on the user providing the glimpse: If you get a glimpse request from someone, you have to remember to respond the next time you're at a laptop. And making the job harder for the glimpse provider is worse than making the job harder for the glimpse requester. In asymmetrical communication use cases (e.g., mom-college kid), the user more interested in communication (mom) is going to be more likely to request a glimpse, so the less-motivated user (son) will be the glimpse provider. To make this communication work, the less-motivated user has to have a really easy job.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Our team does not have a background in mobile, but this feature was too significant too ignore. So we're off to become semi-competent mobile developers!</p>
    </div>
